  "doc_id": "47788",
  "text": "The case-only design is a powerful method for analyzing gene-bygene interaction effects on longevity [CITATION_1] provided that the two genetic variants are not in linkage disequilibrium (LD). The method is characterized by assessment of interaction effects without controls, an important feature in longevity studies as compared with the traditional case-control design [CITATION_2] for which the longevity phenotype in the young controls are actually censored. Similar to all association analyses, current application of the case-only design encounters problem of multiple testing due to the popularity of the single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) markers. The situation is further complicated by the correlated structure among SNPs typed in each of the interacting genes. Resampling-based methods have been applied in analyzing microarray gene expression data for P value adjustment accounting for multiplicity and dependence structure in the thousands of genes tested simultaneously in a microarray experiment using the case-control design [CITATION_3] . In the case-only analysis of gene-gene interactions (G 9 G), the popular phenotype-based permutation test for multiple comparisons is inapplicable as all samples are of the same phenotype, that is, cases. This paper aims at first introducing a novel genotype-based permutation scheme to the case-only analysis of G 9 G using multiple SNPs genotyped in each of the interacting genes and second, applying the method to SNPs data on FOXO1a and FOXO3a genes in the Danish 1905 birth cohort who survived over 93 years of age.",
